making such a report?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A belief supported by both subjective concern and objective observations","A belief based on authoritative guidelines alone","A belief derived from personal intuition","A belief shared by other staff members","A belief based on previous encounters only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebelief supported by both subjective concern and objective observations\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes what constitutes a reasonable belief for reporting concerns. This combines the healthcare professional\u0027s genuine concern with specific, observable behaviours or incidents that would convince an objective third party that there is reason to believe the perceived impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA belief based on authoritative guidelines alone\u003C/strong\u003E does not incorporate specific observations of the current situation and lacks contextual assessment. While guidelines are important reference points, they must be applied to specific circumstances with supporting evidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA belief derived from personal intuition\u003C/strong\u003E lacks the necessary objective evidence required to substantiate concerns about a colleague\u0027s fitness to practise. Intuition may prompt further investigation but cannot stand alone as justification for formal reporting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA belief shared by other staff members\u003C/strong\u003E may simply reflect collective bias or group dynamics rather than a properly reasoned assessment based on evidence. Consensus does not equate to validity without supporting objective observations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA belief based on previous encounters only\u003C/strong\u003E disregards current circumstances and fails to consider whether past issues remain relevant to the present situation. Historical context may inform current concerns but cannot be the sole basis for action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen considering whether to report concerns about a colleague, healthcare professionals must be able to articulate specific observations and incidents that support their concerns, not just feelings or impressions. This ensures that reports are made responsibly and with appropriate justification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A reasonable belief requires both subjective conviction and objective supporting evidence.","Healthcare professionals must be able to justify their beliefs based on credible information and rational analysis.","The standard for reasonable belief in healthcare is higher than mere personal opinion or intuition."],"references":["\u0022What is \u2018BELIEF ON REASONABLE GROUNDS?\u2019\u0022 Swain PA. 1998. Available from: https://classic.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/AltLawJl/1998/90.pdf","Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61016"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61016"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T22:20:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T22:20:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10798"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75506"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"